# Introduction
  
  **Paper**: DeepMSPeptide: peptide detectability prediction using deep learning

  **Citation**: Guillermo Serrano, Elizabeth Guruceaga, Victor Segura, DeepMSPeptide: peptide detectability prediction using deep learning, Bioinformatics, Volume 36, Issue 4, February 2020, Pages 1279â€“1280, https://doi.org/10.1093/bioinformatics/btz708

  
  The problem space is on proteomics which is the study of the interactions, function, composition, and structures of proteins. Protein detection and quantification are important areas for studying and understanding cellular biology and diseases. Peptide detectability is an important issue but it is difficult to quantify because of the larger number of variables involved in detecting certain peptide or amino acid sequences. Current methods use standard samples or sets of identified peptides in different biological samples.

  This paper proposes DeepMSPeptide, which is a bioinformatic tool to predict peptide detectability based on peptide amino acid sequences. It uses a multi-layer approach with convolutional layers (1D-2C-CNN and 1D-1C-CNN). The paper provided results of the work and metrics that were compared with other works and is shown later. This contribution is important to this problem area as it is the first time that a DL approach was used with only the amino acid sequence and not requiring the physicochemical properties.

# Scope of Reproducibility:

List hypotheses from the paper you will test and the corresponding experiments you will run.


Hypothesis 1: The DeepMSPeptide deep learning model can improve peptide detectability compared to existing models

Steps to set up and conduct this hypothesis:

##  Data

The input data for training the model was from the GPMDB database. The data represents the peptide sequence as amino acids which are written as a sequence of their 1-letter codes (shown below). This input vector is then converted into an integer using the dictionary shown in the data processing code that assigns an integer to each amino acid. Since peptides have different lengths, a 0 padding is introduced with a max length set at 81 amino acids.

-

![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)

##   Model And Training

**Model architecture:**

- First layer: An embedding layer will be used to process the input tensor.
- Second layer: Dropout layer to randomly set a fraction of the input units to 0 at each epoch of the training (prevents over-fitting)
- Third layer: One or two 1D convolutional layers with 64 filters, a sliding window of 1, and a width of 3.
- Fourth layer: Two hidden layers

Detailed model information using summary function.

![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)


**Training objectives:**

The model was trained using a binary cross entropy loss function. Training was done with 200 epochs in batches of 100 samples. Training was stopped if the loss function stabilized within 5 consecutive epochs. The dropout rate was set at 0.2.

Next step would be to take a new dataset from the DbyDeep: Exploration of MS-Detectable Peptides via Deep Learning [2]. The dataset there will be useful to perform the external evaluation of the model. The dataset needs to be processed first. The evaluation results for this dataset are shown in the next section.

# Loading the input and assigning integers to each 1-letter amino acid code
# Extracting the label value too
def load_pep_and_codify_labels(file, max_len):
  aa_dict={'A':1,'R':2,'N':3,'D':4,'C':5,'Q':6,'E':7,'G':8,'H':9,'I':10,'L':11,'K':12,'M':13,'F':14,'P':15,'O':16,'S':17,'U':18,'T':19,'W':20,'Y':21,'V':22}
  with open(file, 'r') as inf:
    next(inf)
    lines = inf.read().splitlines()
  pep_codes=[]
  long_pep_counter = 0
  newLines = []

  labels = []

  trueCount = 0
  falseCount = 0

  for line in lines:
    line = line.split(',')
    pep = line[0]
    label = line[5]
    if not len(pep) > max_len:
      current_pep=[]
      for aa in pep:
        current_pep.append(aa_dict[aa])
      pep_codes.append(current_pep)
      newLines.extend([pep])

      if label == 'True':
        labels.append(1)
        trueCount += 1
      else:
        labels.append(0)
        falseCount += 1
    else:
      long_pep_counter += 1
  predict_data = keras.preprocessing.sequence.pad_sequences(pep_codes, value=0, padding='post', maxlen=max_len)

  print(trueCount)
  print(falseCount)

  return predict_data, labels, newLines

print('Loading input...')
predict_data, labels, lines = load_pep_and_codify_labels('/content/drive/MyDrive/CS598-Deep/data/test.csv', 81)
print('Succesfully loaded {0} peptides!'.format(len(lines)))

labels = np.array(labels)

predictions = model_2_1D.predict(predict_data)

It seems that the new dataset has an accuracy of around 0.75 which is slightly lower than the accuracy shown in the paper. The image below is the classification report for the new dataset while the image below that is the taken results from the paper. More work may need to be done in the future to complete new abalations. However, the initial results seem to prove that this model is better at predicting peptide detectability than the others listed, even when testing it with a new dataset.

# Discussion

Based on my experimental results, it seems like the model proposed in this paper is better at predicting peptide detectability than previous models. Even when I evaluated the model on an external dataset I found that the accuracy was 0.75 and the f1-scores were 0.73 and 0.77. This was lower than the results obtained by the author but was still higher than previous models, such as, the Gaussian, Nnet, RF, and SvmR models. These results were relatively easy to reproduce from the original paper as the method for handling input data and running the model was straight forward. The authors also provided a public repository with the raw data and code which made it easy to follow their methods. That being said, it was still difficult to understand the model because not much information was given, especially information on training and model parameters. My recommendation to the authors would be to add additional information on the model and training in their methods section. I would also encourage them to add more comments to document their code.
